SIMPLE: obligate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obligate
<hw>Ob"li*gate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Obligated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Obligating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>obligatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>obligare</ets>. See
<er>Oblige</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring or place under
obligation, moral or legal; to hold by a constraining motive.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Obligated</xex> by a sense of duty.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Proudfit.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That's your true plan -- to <qex>obligate</qex>⟦br⟧
The present ministers of state.</q> <rj><qau>Churchill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bind or firmly hold to an act; to compel; to
constrain; to bind to any act of duty or courtesy by a formal
pledge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That they may not incline or be <qex>obligated</qex> to any vile
or lowly occupations.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>obligated</ent>⟦br⟧
